===Table===
This table shows which video formats that are ''likely'' to be supported by a given [[user agent]]. Most of the browsers listed here use a [[multimedia framework]] for decoding and display of video, instead of incorporating such software components. It is not generally possible to tell the set of formats supported by a multimedia framework without querying it, because that depends on the [[operating system]] and third party codecs. &lt;ref name=&quot;phonon-backs&quot;&gt;{{citation |url=http://doc.qt.nokia.com/latest/phonon-overview.html#backends |title=Phonon documentation of backends |accessdate=2011-06-3 |publisher=Qt}}&lt;/ref&gt; In these cases, video format support is an attribute of the framework, not the browser (or its layout engine), assuming the browser properly queries its multimedia framework before rejecting unknown video formats. In some cases, the support listed here is not a function of either codecs available within the operating system's underlying media framework, or of codec capabilities built in to the browser, but rather could be by a browser add-on that might, for example, bypass the browser's normal HTML parsing of the &lt;video&gt; tag to embed a plug-in based video player.

The video format can be specified by [[Internet media type|MIME type]] in HTML (see [[#Multiple_sources|example]]). MIME types are used for querying multimedia frameworks for supported formats. {{#tag:ref|at least for [[Phonon (KDE)|Phonon]] and its backends &lt;ref name=&quot;phonon-query&quot;&gt;{{citation |url=http://doc.qt.nokia.com/latest/phonon-overview.html#querying-backends-for-support |title=Phonon documentation of querying |accessdate=2011-06-3 |publisher=Qt}}&lt;/ref&gt;, that is [[DirectShow]], [[QuickTime]] and [[GStreamer]]|group=note|name=Phonon-docs}}

Of these browsers, only Firefox, Opera and Origyn employ libraries for built-in decoding. In practice, Internet Explorer and Safari can also guarantee certain format support, because their manufacturers also make their multimedia frameworks. At the other end of the scale, Konqueror has identical format support to Internet Explorer when run on Windows, and Safari when run on Mac, but the selected support here for Konqueror is the typical for GNU/Linux, where Konqueror has most of its users. In general, the format support of browsers is much dictated by conflicting interests of vendors, specifically that [[Media Foundation]] and [[QuickTime]] support commercial standards, whereas [[GStreamer]] and [[Phonon (KDE)|Phonon]] cannot legally support other than free formats by default on the free operating systems that they are intended for.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}}

